User management
A user is a person who utilizes a computer or network service. Linux is said to be secure 
because one user cannot access files of other user without its permission. There are three types of users
1. Root user/ Super user
	- Root user is a super user in system who has all access pass to the system functionality
2. Standard user
	- Standard user are those user which are created by us and they have limited privileges compared to root user .  local user accounts or standard user accounts are for the people who need to work on a system and who need limited access to the resources on that system.
3. System User
	- System user is a user account created by the system rather than a regular user who used to run background processes and services. These user accounts typically have a password that is used for authenticating the user to the system. 
